title: PRODUCT LAUNCH AT BENGALURU TECH SUMMIT 2025
description:
Vayuvya Defence at Bengaluru Tech Summit 2025 | Showcasing Our Indigenous Jet Engine at the LEAP Pavilion (Hosted by KDEM) 

We are proud to present highlights from our showcase at the Bengaluru Tech Summit, where Vayuvya Defence exhibited its indigenously designed miniature jet engine at the prestigious LEAP Pavilion, hosted by KDEM (Karnataka Digital Economy Mission).

This platform gave us the opportunity to demonstrate our commitment to Indiaâ€™s growing aerospace and defence innovation landscape. Our jet engineâ€”created for education, research, and early-stage propulsion understandingâ€”received overwhelming interest from students, researchers, industry leaders, and technology enthusiasts.


---

  Meet the Team Behind Vayuvya Defence

Our jet engine project is the result of months of deep research, rigorous engineering, and a passion to make aerospace learning accessible in India.

ğŸ”¹ Prashanth Raghu â€” Co-founder & CEO

The visionary who initiated this journey through detailed mathematical modelling. His strategic leadership and analytical foundation laid the directional roadmap for the engineâ€™s architecture and performance goals.

ğŸ”¹ Dhanush D B â€” Co-founder & CTO

The technical driving force behind the project. Dhanush led the full design, development, and engineering finalisation, converting theoretical models into a practical, test-ready jet engine. His expertise turned concepts into a functional prototype.

ğŸ”¹ Raghavendra G â€” Co-founder & Head of Engineering

The backbone of the core engineering research. Raghavendra conducted the base research, feasibility studies, material analysis, and was responsible for crafting the initial and advanced design layers of the engine. His work ensured that the foundation of the engine was technically strong and robust.

Together, this team represents a blend of vision, engineering depth, and hands-on innovationâ€”driving Vayuvya Defence forward.


---

  Special Thanks to KDEM

We extend our sincere gratitude to KDEM for providing us the opportunity to exhibit at the LEAP Pavilion and for continuously supporting Karnatakaâ€™s deep-tech and aerospace startup ecosystem.


---

   About Vayuvya Defence

Vayuvya Defence is dedicated to building accessible aerospace technologies for learning, research, prototyping, and future defence applications. We aim to empower Indiaâ€™s next generation of engineers with cutting-edge, indigenous propulsion systems.


---

title: FibriTimer Zeta 2  - Two channel coagulation analyzer Product Launch at BTS25, Leap pavilion, BIEL.
description:
Dfine Bio-Innovations Pvt Ltd  is a MedTech Start-up from Bangalore focussed on indigenously developing affordable, leading-edge medical devices for small â€“ mid size clinical laboratories globally. The startup co-founded by a 4-member team whose cumulative industry experience is more than 60 years is ISO 13485, ZED certified, DPIIT registered, CDSCO licensed and holding many technology, design patents.

Our Quantifiable Goal is to enable at least 7,000 clinical laboratories to perform advanced diagnostic tests in-house by 2027, improving test turnaround times and patient outcomes, and our Vision is to achieve Rs.100 crore in revenue by 2030.

In the heart of Indiaâ€™s bustling healthcare industry, where 80% of medical devices are imported and operational costs are skyrocketing innovation was long overdue for the often-neglected laboratories in smaller tiers. Enter FibriTimer Zeta-1, a trailblazing semi-automated coagulation analyzer that is transforming coagulation diagnostics in rural India.

Developed by Dfine Bioinnovations Pvt Ltd, FibriTimer Zeta-1 is Indiaâ€™s first indigenous coagulation analyzer that combines affordability, precision, and innovation, addressing critical gaps in coagulation diagnostics. Built with patented dual technology that integrates optical and mechanical methods on a single platform to boost reporting confidence and help user with a expanded test menu. Zeta â€“ 1, delivers accurate results for vital tests such as PT/APTT, Fibrinogen, Lupus, and D-dimer and more. Today we offer three variants in semi-automated coagulation system and will be adding more variants in soon time. We also intend to develop a 4 channel semi-automated coagulation system and alongside have ambitious plans to venture into developing a series of world-class automated coagulation systems by early 2027. 

The future is promising for those who are steadfast in their ambitions and goalsâ€¦ and we intend to write our tomorrowâ€¦ Today!!!   

Today at bangalore international exhibition center where the the government of Karnataka is hosting its ambitious annual tech summit   BTS2025 we at Dfine bioinnovations is proud to be a part of this mega event and had an opportunity to LAUNCH our newest model of coagulation testing semi automated device named FIBRITIMER ZETA - 2M - A mechanical technology testing device for small clinical laboratories with two independent channels for testing coagulation plasma samples be it individually or in duplicate testing mode. title: Meet Keo - India's low cost AI-powered computer for just â‚¹18,999
description:
While the world debates whether AI will replace jobs, the Govt of Karnataka just asked a better question: what if millions of kids never get to learn AI in the first place?
Hereâ€™s what most people donâ€™t know - the digital divide isnâ€™t just about having a computer anymore. Itâ€™s about having access to the tools that will define the next decade.
So Karnataka Govt run company Keonics built Keo - a tech that runs AI locally (no internet needed!), using open-source everything, at an affordable price point - indicating that its not just a product launch but a policy shift
Their AI Buddh is trained on actual school syllabus. Imagine a student in a village asking their computer to explain a physics concept and getting an answer that matches what their textbook teaches. Thatâ€™s contextual AI. Thatâ€™s what makes this different.
This isnâ€™t about replacing expensive computers. Itâ€™s about creating a generation that doesnâ€™t have to wait for privilege to learn the skills that matter.

title: Five Nights at Freddy's 2 | A First Look
description:
Taking it to a whole new level. Five Nights at Freddyâ€™s 2 only in theaters December 5. Get tickets now: https://www.fivenightsatfreddys.movie/


In 2023, Blumhouseâ€™s box-office horror phenomenon Five Nights at Freddyâ€™s, based on the blockbuster game series by Scott Cawthon, became the highest-grossing horror film of the year. Now, a shocking new chapter of animatronic terror begins. 
 
One year has passed since the supernatural nightmare at Freddy Fazbearâ€™s Pizza. The stories about what transpired there have been twisted into a campy local legend, inspiring the townâ€™s first ever Fazfest. 
 
Former security guard Mike (Josh Hutcherson) and police officer Vanessa (Elizabeth Lail) have kept the truth from Mikeâ€™s 11-year-old sister, Abby (Piper Rubio), concerning the fate of her animatronic friends. 
 
But when Abby sneaks out to reconnect with Freddy, Bonnie, Chica, and Foxy, it will set into motion a terrifying series of events, revealing dark secrets about the true origin of Freddyâ€™s, and unleashing a long-forgotten horror hidden away for decades.
 
The cast of Five Nights at Freddyâ€™s 2 includes returning co-stars Theodus Crane as Jeremiah and the legendary Matthew Lillard as William Afton. The film features new characters played by Freddy Carter (Shadow and Bone, Pennyworth), Wayne Knight (Jurassic Park, Seinfeld), Mckenna Grace (Ghostbusters franchise, Annabelle Comes Home) and horror icon Skeet Ulrich (Scream, Riverdale). 
 
Five Nights at Freddyâ€™s 2 is directed by acclaimed returning filmmaker Emma Tammi and is written by game series creator Scott Cawthon.
 
The film is produced by Blumhouse founder and CEO Jason Blum and Scott Cawthon, who together produced the first film. The executive producers are director Emma Tammi, Beatriz Sequeira, Christopher Warner, Russell Binder and Marc Mostman. 
 
The first Freddyâ€™s film opened to a record-shattering $80 million in October 2023 and went on to earn almost $300 million worldwide.

The inspiration behind this video: 

No one would have expected an animated children's movie about the K-pop industry would break records on music charts and would become the most-watched Netflix original content in the history of the OTT platform, but Sony Animation Studio's KPop Demon Hunters has achieved the seemingly impossible. Its catchy soundtrack has taken the world by storm and even made Billboard records.

KPop Demon Hunters is a modern movie that will reshape the industry by helping the animated musical genre become bigger than it's ever been. title: Innovation Spotlight: Randa Mudathir, MSc
description: Meet Randa Mudathir, MSc. Randa is the CEO and Co-Founder of NovaSonix Healthcare Inc. She is the 2024 First Place Winner of the ORS Business Innovation Competition Award. Randa completed her master's at Western University in Medical Biophysics, where her work bridged medical imaging and biomedical innovation. Through NovaSonix Healthcare, Randa is transforming MSK imaging with the MSKNovaVue, an attachment that turns a standard ultrasound machine into a real-time 3D scanner.

title: UWM Innovation Spotlight: Solar Tech
description:
Introducing a new class of solar materials made from low-cost, water-based phosphate coatings that act like semiconductors and can be applied directly to metals like steel and copper. These solid-state coatings absorb blue light, generate electricity, and eliminate traditional liquid electrolytesâ€”making solar scalable, durable, and affordable. From rooftops to industrial surfaces, this breakthrough opens the door to embedded energy generation in ways never seen before.

Inventors: Drs. Nikolai Kouklin and Konstantin Sobolev from the @uw-milwaukee

#solar #energy #innovation #techtransfer

title: Raizer II Emergency Lifting Chair Featured on ThirdAge.Design Podcast
description:
Our Falls Recovery team recently had the opportunity to discuss the significant impact Raizer II is having on the lives of older adults, on the ThirdAge.Design podcast, during their Innovation Spotlight segment.

As a simple, battery-operated mobile lifting chair, Raizer II enables a fallen individual to be raised to an almost standing position in just 30 seconds. Designed for ease of use, the chair can be assembled and operated by a single person, making it an essential solution for both care professionals and family members.

During the podcast, the team explained how Raizer II is helping to improve quality of care by offering practical, effective support in emergency situations. Thanks to Lori Pinkerton-Rolet for inviting us to share our story and for facilitating an engaging conversation about this innovative solution.

title: The History of AI Explained: Crash Course Futures of AI #1
description:
In 1965, Mooreâ€™s Law predicted how computers would become smaller, faster, and more powerful than ever before. But here in 2025, weâ€™re on the brink of an even bigger revolution. Introduction 00:00
How did AI get here? 2:21
How do we measure AI progress? 7:47
How can we predict the future of AI? 9:10
Conclusion 11:29

About This Series:
AI is changing FAST so rather than doing a full Crash Course series of 12+ episodes, weâ€™ve prepared a mini-series of just the basics. Crash Course will never tell you what to think and weâ€™re not the type of organization that responds to breaking news in real time. Instead, weâ€™re here to offer a zoomed-out foundation upon which to base your own opinions as you continue to learn from other outlets about the world thatâ€™s changing around us.

-What even is AI? Whatâ€™s the history of this thing and how quickly has it evolved to what exists today?
-How could AI transform society? Will AI cause the next Industrial Revolution, and what might that mean for workers and the environment?
-How powerful could AI become? How do we measure the progression of AI? What are the consequences weâ€™re already seeing, and what might be the future consequences of unchecked AI development?

title: AI Explained: What is Tokenization in NLP?
description:
Foundational Concepts of NLP Tokenization
This video explains Tokenization, the fundamental process that allows AI and computers to understand human language by breaking it down into smaller, manageable pieces called "tokens."

The Problem: Computers understand numbers, not the nuances of human language (slang, grammar, emotion). Tokenization bridges this gap by translating messy text into a structured format.

Types of Tokenization:

Word Tokenization: Splits text into individual words and punctuation (useful for word frequency analysis).

Sentence Tokenization: Breaks paragraphs into complete sentences (useful for summarization).

Advanced Methods: It introduces Subword Tokenization (used by models like GPT and BERT), which breaks complex or unknown words into smaller meaningful parts (e.g., "tokenization" becomes "token" + "##ization") to handle new words and typos effectively.

The "Chef" Analogy: The video compares tokenization to a chef prepping ingredientsâ€”chopping and slicing language before the AI can "cook" up an answer.

title: How Wearable Tech Will Heighten Our Senses and Abilities, with Pedro Lopes
description:
Can you imagine a world in which a wearable device, like a smartwatch, could move your fingers to strum the guitar or play the drums? That kind of technology is part of the innovative research coming out of the Human-Computer Integration Lab at the University of Chicago, led by renowned computer scientist Pedro Lopes. His lab is developing a new generation of gadgets that use haptics (or tactile sensations like the buzz of your smartphone) to move your body, replicate your sense of smell and even make you feel things.


In this episode, Lopes explores the potential of wearable devices to transform our future as well as brain-computer interfaces that are being developed by companies like Elon Muskâ€™s Neuralink that directly into the body.

2. Symbol Meaning: The BMW roundelâ€™s blue and white sections reflect Bavariaâ€™s colors and connect to the brandâ€™s early aviation heritage.

3. Tech Leadership: BMW leads in innovation with electric models like the BMW i3 and advanced driver-assistance technologies.

4. Motorsport Legacy: BMWâ€™s M division highlights the brandâ€™s racing excellence, producing high-performance vehicles known for speed and precision.

5. Worldwide Influence: BMW has a strong global presence, serving customers across multiple continents.

6. Premium Craftsmanship: BMW is recognized for blending luxury, comfort, and advanced engineering in every vehicle.

ABOUT LUDICROUS FEED

Ludicrous Feed is a Sydney-based YouTube channel showing daily life as an Australian family with an electric vehicle.

Tom and Joy provide straightforward candid insights into key issues around EV adoption such as vehicle range, charging infrastructure and road trip planning.

The channel started in 2018 after Tom purchased his Tesla Model S. The weekly live stream provides an opportunity for audience members to engage with others from the EV community as well as to stay up to date with the latest industry news. They have a Sigenergy home battery coupled with rooftop solar and together have reviewed many electric vehicles for the channel including brands such as BYD, Geely (Polestar, Volvo, Zeekr, Smart), Hyundai Motor Group (Kia, Genesis), SAIC (MG, LDV), GWM, Stellantis (Leapmotor, Peugeot, Fiat, Abarth, Jeep), VW Group (Cupra, Skoda), BMW Group (Rolls Royce, Mini), GM (Cadillac), Ford, Toyota, Subaru, Nissan, Renault, Xpeng, Chery and Deepal.

title: Ford UK Boss Warns Against Higher Taxes on Electric Vehicles: Will It Hurt EV Adoption?
description:
Lisa Brankin, Managing Director of Ford UK, has issued a stark warning to Rachel Reeves about the potential impact of higher taxes on electric vehicles (EVs). With reports suggesting a new pay-per-mile charge for EVs from 2028, Brankin argues that such measures could discourage drivers from making the switch to electric. This comes at a critical time when the UK government aims for 80% of new vehicle sales to be EVs by 2030. In this video, we break down the key points of Brankin's argument, the proposed tax changes, and what they mean for the future of electric vehicles in the UK. We also discuss the role of government incentives, the current state of EV demand, and the challenges faced by automakers like Ford. Whether you're an EV owner, considering going electric, or just interested in the future of transportation, this video provides essential insights into the ongoing debate.
Key topics covered:
- Ford UK's stance on EV taxation
- The proposed pay-per-mile charge for EVs
- Impact on consumer demand for electric vehicles
- Government targets and incentives for EV adoption

title: EV angst, NZ Geo confronts financial fragility | Mediawatch
description:
EVs were booming, but incentives have been stripped back and recent reports of fires have fueled safety fears. Has media coverage amped up the danger? Also: a year ago a NZ Geographic revealed its own flaky finances to persuade supporters to step up. How did that work out? 
Read more (https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/mediawatch) about this episode of Mediawatch on the RNZ website
In this episode:
1:06 For a while the EV market boomed with incentives in place, though they came at a cost. Now the incentives have been dialled down - and so has demand. And a steady stream of stories about the fire hazards have spread like wildfire.
13:18: Dr Troy Bailsden on how to â€˜pre-bunkâ€™ alarmism about EV safety - and where to find facts on the real but remote risks of batteries.
19:51: Magazines devoted to longform journalism are struggling to stay in print. A year ago award-winning NZ Geographic urged subscribers to up their backing to keep it going. One year on publisher James Frankham on how that worked out - and whatâ€™s next.
Learn more: Mediawatch: Angst about EVs blows up in the headlines | RNZ News (https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/579729/mediawatch-angst-about-evs-blows-up-in-the-headlines)
Guests: Troy Baisden, James Frankham
Follow Mediawatch and listen on Apple Podcasts, Spotify or any podcast app to make sure you never miss an episode.
Find more RNZ Podcasts at the new section of the RNZ website at rnz.co.nz/podcasts (https://www.rnz.co.nz/podcasts)


Go to this episode on rnz.co.nz for more details (https://www.rnz.co.nz/podcast/mediawatch?share=0fc8e854-476a-4b94-a849-ecfac17b8e35)




To listen to more RNZ Podcasts, subscribe here: @rnzpodcasts1325

New Dutch Food: Innovation Meets Sustainability
description:
In this episode of Orange Horizons, we explore the rise of New Dutch Food. A movement that blends innovation, sustainability, and creativity into every bite.
 

Join host Alix Perry as we travel from smart farms and seaweed kitchens to multicultural food markets, discovering how the Netherlands is reinventing its culinary identity. You'll hear from Michelin-starred chefs, farmers, and innovators how are reshaping the menu for a sustainable tomorrow.
 Key themes in this episode 
      
  â€¢   
     
     How innovation drives sustainable agriculture and food production.
      
      
  â€¢   
     
     The rise of food forests and circular restaurants.
      
      
  â€¢   
     
     Seaweed as the new sustainable superfood.
      
      
  â€¢   
     
     Diversity and cultural influences shaping the Dutch kitchen.
      
      
  â€¢   
     
     How the Netherlands became a test lab for the future of food.
      
       

Hungry for more?
 Visit holland.com/food (https://www.holland.com/food)  for culinary travel tips, local experiences, and the best places to literally taste the future.
 



 

Orange Horizons is the official podcast by Netherlands Board of Tourism & Conventions, taking you beyond the guidebooks. In each episode, we explore inspiring stories and locations from the heart of Dutch culture, innovation and sustainability. From groundbreaking architecture to local art, design, and green travel experiences. Discover what makes the Netherlands truly unique, and let us inspire your next unforgettable journey to the Netherlands.
 

Follow us in your favorite podcast app and visit holland.com (http://holland.com)  for more ideas, tips, and stories.

In this episode, we connect food, innovation, and economic development: from traditional noodles to the invention of instant ramen in 1958, the packaging breakthrough of Cup Noodles in 1971, and the explosive regional adaptations that followed in Japan, Korea, Thailand, Indonesia, Taiwan, and China. You will meet the key inventor, the powerhouse brands, and the retail and logistics systems that turned a humble cup into a worldwide phenomenon.

What you will learn

The culinary roots of noodles in East and Southeast Asia, and how postwar Japan incubated the â€œinstantâ€ leap.

1958: Momofuku Andoâ€™s Chikin Ramen and the flash-frying method that made safe, tasty noodles shelf-stable.

1971: Why Cup Noodles was a packaging revolution (the cup as pot, bowl, and brand).

How convenience stores, vending machines, hot-water access, and modern supply chains enabled mass adoption.

Regional spin-offs: Korean ramyeon heat, Thai Tom Yum profiles, Indonesian mie goreng sweetness, Taiwanese and Chinese retail scale.

Culture and soft power: museums, viral challenges, and how flavors narrate nation brands.

Health note: like anything, excess is not recommended; today there are air-dried, lower-sodium, veggie-boosted options.

Key brands, people, and terms 
Nissin â€¢ Cup Noodles â€¢ Top Ramen â€¢ Maruchan â€¢ Momofuku Ando â€¢ Chikin Ramen (1958) â€¢ Cup Noodles (1971) â€¢ Indomie (mie goreng) â€¢ Nongshim (Shin Ramyun) â€¢ Samyang (Buldak â€œfire noodlesâ€) â€¢ Maggi noodles â€¢ Mama (Thai President Foods) â€¢ Uni-President â€¢ Master Kong / Tingyi â€¢ Ottogi â€¢ Paldo â€¢ â€œramen vs ramyeonâ€ â€¢ Cup Noodles Museum (Yokohama, Ikeda) â€¢ konbini (Japanese convenience stores) â€¢ Japan vending machines â€¢ Asian economic miracle â€¢ innovation frugality â€¢ supply-chain logistics.

Questions we answer

Who invented instant noodles and why did it happen in 1958?

What changed in 1971 that made the cup format â€œchange everythingâ€?

How did urbanization + convenience + logistics equal mass adoption?

Why did Korea, Thailand, Indonesia, Taiwan, and China adapt the format so quickly?

Is it only about price, or also taste, time, distribution, and branding?

Are instant noodles unhealthy? How to use them smartly and what better variants exist today?

Chapters
0Hookâ€”three minutes that reshaped eating
From traditional bowl to global phenomenon
Momofuku Ando and Chicken Ramen
Cup Noodles: packaging as innovation
Korea, Thailand, Indonesia: local flavors + scale
Taiwan and China: retail modernization and distribution muscle
The equation: urbanization + convenience + logistics = adoption
Brands, culture, and edible soft power
Health context and smarter choices
Three lessons beyond food
Closingâ€” three-minute story

Why this matters
Instant noodles are not just â€œcheap food.â€ They are a masterclass in how tradition + design + manufacturing + retail can create an industry, free up time for workers and students, support disaster relief, and project culture globallyâ€”while continuously innovating on flavor, format, and nutrition.

What was your first instant noodle brandâ€”and which flavor still wins for you? Drop it below and tell us where you are watching from.

If you love the intersection of food, innovation, and economics, subscribe for more.
